1 AN ACT
2 RELATING TO HEALTH CARE PROFESSIONAL LOAN REPAYMENT;
3 REQUIRING AWARD RECIPIENTS TO BE HEALTH PROFESSIONALS WHO
4 CURRENTLY MAINTAIN PRACTICE IN NEW MEXICO OR AGREE TO
5 RELOCATE TO AND COMMENCE PRACTICE IN NEW MEXICO; REQUIRING
6 THE HIGHER EDUCATION DEPARTMENT TO DETERMINE AND DISBURSE
7 AWARD AMOUNTS; PROVIDING ADDITIONAL AWARD CRITERIA; ADDING
8 DEFINITIONS; ALLOWING FEES TO BE ASSESSED UPON BREACH OF
9 CONTRACT; AMENDING THE HEALTH PROFESSIONAL LOAN REPAYMENT
10 FUND; REPEALING SECTIONS OF THE NMSA 1978; MAKING AN
11 APPROPRIATION.
12
13 BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF THE STATE OF NEW MEXICO:
14 SECTION 1. Section 21-22D-3 NMSA 1978 (being Laws 1995,
15 Chapter 144, Section 18, as amended) is amended to read:
16 "21-22D-3. DEFINITIONS.--As used in the Health
17 Professional Loan Repayment Act:
18 A. "award" means the grant of money to repay
19 eligible education debt;
20 B. "department" means the higher education
21 department;
22 C. "health professional" means a professional
23 licensed pursuant to the:
24 (1) Medical Practice Act;
25 (2) Physical Therapy Act; HHHC/HB 66/a
Page 1

1 (3) Occupational Therapy Act;
2 (4) Speech-Language Pathology, Audiology and
3 Hearing Aid Dispensing Practices Act;
4 (5) Pharmacy Act;
5 (6) Nutrition and Dietetics Practice Act;
6 (7) Respiratory Care Act;
7 (8) Medical Imaging and Radiation Therapy
8 Health and Safety Act;
9 (9) Dental Health Care Act;
10 (10) Professional Psychologist Act;
11 (11) Counseling and Therapy Practice Act;
12 (12) Nursing Practice Act;
13 (13) Optometry Act;
14 (14) Chiropractic Physician Practice Act;
15 (15) Dental Amalgam Waste Reduction Act;
16 (16) Genetic Counseling Act;
17 (17) Polysomnography Practice Act;
18 (18) Physician Assistant Act;
19 (19) Anesthesiologist Assistants Act;
20 (20) Podiatry Act;
21 (21) Professional Psychologist Act;
22 (22) Pharmacist Prescriptive Authority Act;
23 (23) Massage Therapy Practice Act;
24 (24) Acupuncture and Oriental Medicine
25 Practice Act; HHHC/HB 66/a
Page 2

1 (25) Social Work Practice Act;
2 (26) Emergency Medical Services Act; and
3 (27) other health professional licensing
4 acts as determined by the department;
5 D. "licensed physician" means a health
6 professional who is licensed to practice medicine in New
7 Mexico pursuant to the Medical Practice Act;
8 E. "loan" means a grant of money to defray the
9 costs incidental to a health education, under a contract
10 between the federal government or a commercial lender and a
11 health professional, requiring either repayment of principal
12 and interest or repayment in services; and
13 F. "nurse in advanced practice" means a registered
14 nurse, including a:
15 (1) certified nurse practitioner, certified
16 registered nurse anesthetist or clinical nurse specialist,
17 authorized pursuant to the Nursing Practice Act to function
18 beyond the scope of practice of professional registered
19 nursing; or
20 (2) certified nurse-midwife licensed by the
21 department of health."
22 SECTION 2. Section 21-22D-6 NMSA 1978 (being Laws 1995,
23 Chapter 144, Section 21, as amended) is amended to read:
24 "21-22D-6. HEALTH PROFESSIONAL LOAN REPAYMENT PROGRAM--
25 AWARD CRITERIA--CONTRACT TERMS--PAYMENT.-- HHHC/HB 66/a
Page 3

1 A. The "health professional loan repayment
2 program" is created and shall be administered by the
3 department. A health professional shall apply for an award
4 on a form provided by the department.
5 B. Health professionals shall be selected to
6 receive awards based on the following criteria:
7 (1) a health professional shall currently
8 maintain practice in New Mexico or have agreed to relocate to
9 and commence practice in New Mexico within ninety days of the
10 grant of an award. An award shall not be disbursed until the
11 health professional commences practice in New Mexico;
12 (2) highest priority shall be given to
13 licensed physicians;
14 (3) designated health professional shortage
15 areas and a health professional's total eligible education
16 debt and characteristics of the practice; and
17 (4) the number of awards shall be limited to
18 the amount of funds appropriated to the department for the
19 purpose of the health professional loan repayment program.
20 C. Award amounts shall be determined by the
21 department in accordance with the following:
22 (1) funds shall be disbursed in amounts that
23 result in the payment of the full obligation of all awards
24 provided in a given year;
25 (2) an award to a licensed physician shall HHHC/HB 66/a
Page 4

1 be a minimum of seventy-five thousand dollars ($75,000) per
2 year for four consecutive years, with the exception that:
3 (a) the total award amount shall not
4 exceed the licensed physician's total eligible education
5 debt;
6 (b) the award amount shall be prorated
7 based on a four-year award period; and
8 (c) part-time employment as a licensed
9 physician shall be prorated based on the percentage of hours
10 worked relative to full-time employment; and
11 (3) an award to a health professional other
12 than a licensed physician shall:
13 (a) not exceed the health
14 professional's total eligible education debt;
15 (b) be prorated based on a three-year
16 award period; and
17 (c) be prorated based on the percentage
18 of hours relative to full-time employment if the health
19 professional maintains part-time employment in the health
20 professional's respective health profession.
21 D. The department shall encumber the full amount
22 of the award during the first year of a health professional's
23 award period at a published schedule as determined by the
24 department.
25 E. The following education debts are not eligible HHHC/HB 66/a
Page 5

1 for repayment pursuant to the Health Professional Loan
2 Repayment Act:
3 (1) amounts incurred as a result of
4 participation in state loan-for-service programs or other
5 state programs whose purpose states that service be provided
6 in exchange for financial assistance;
7 (2) scholarships that have a service
8 component or obligation;
9 (3) personal loans; and
10 (4) loans that exceed individual standard
11 school expense levels.
12 F. The loan repayment award shall be evidenced by
13 a contract between the health professional and the department
14 acting on behalf of the state. The contract shall provide
15 for the payment by the state of a stated sum to the health
16 professional's debtors and shall state the obligations of the
17 health professional under the program, including a minimum
18 four-year period of service for licensed physicians and
19 three-year period of service for health professionals other
20 than licensed physicians, quarterly reporting requirements
21 and other policies established by the department. The
22 department may cancel the contract made between the
23 department and the health professional for any reasonable
24 cause deemed sufficient by the department.
25 G. Recipients shall serve a complete year in order HHHC/HB 66/a
Page 6

1 to receive credit for that year. The minimum credit for a
2 year shall be established by the department.
3 H. If a health professional does not comply with
4 the terms of the contract, the department shall assess up to
5 the full amount of award disbursed and may assess a fee of no
6 more than eighteen percent interest of the amount of the
7 award disbursed, unless the department finds acceptable
8 extenuating circumstances for why the health professional
9 cannot serve or comply with the terms of the contract. If
10 the department does not find acceptable extenuating
11 circumstances for the health professional's failure to comply
12 with the contract, the department shall require immediate
13 repayment.
14 I. The department shall promulgate rules to
15 implement the provisions of this section that may provide for
16 the disbursement of awards to the lenders of health
17 professionals in annual or other periodic installments."
18 SECTION 3. Section 21-22D-7 NMSA 1978 (being Laws 1995,
19 Chapter 144, Section 22) is amended to read:
20 "21-22D-7. CONTRACTS--ENFORCEMENT.--The general form of
21 the contract required shall be prepared and approved by the
22 attorney general and signed by the health professional and
23 the designated representative of the department on behalf of
24 the state. The department is vested with full and complete
25 authority and power to sue in its own name for any balance HHHC/HB 66/a
Page 7

1 due the state from any student on any such contract."
2 SECTION 4. Section 21-22D-8 NMSA 1978 (being Laws 1995,
3 Chapter 144, Section 23) is amended to read:
4 "21-22D-8. HEALTH PROFESSIONAL LOAN REPAYMENT FUND
5 CREATED--PURPOSE--METHOD OF PAYMENT.--
6 A. The "health professional loan repayment fund"
7 is created as a nonreverting fund in the state treasury. The
8 fund consists of appropriations, distributions, gifts and
9 grants. The department shall administer the fund, and money
10 in the fund is appropriated to the department to provide
11 awards pursuant to the Health Professional Loan Repayment
12 Act; provided that:
13 (1) no less than fifty percent of the
14 available funds in the health professional loan repayment
15 fund as of the beginning of each fiscal year shall be
16 encumbered for licensed physicians who receive an award; and
17 (2) funds that are encumbered but unexpended
18 shall be used for awards in the next fiscal year.
19 B. Disbursements from the fund shall be made by
20 warrant of the secretary of finance and administration
21 pursuant to vouchers signed by the secretary of higher
22 education or the secretary's authorized representative."
23 SECTION 5. Section 21-22D-10 NMSA 1978 (being Laws
24 1995, Chapter 144, Section 25) is amended to read:
25 "21-22D-10. REPORTS.--By December 31 of each year, the HHHC/HB 66/a
Page 8

1 department shall make annual reports to the governor and to
2 the legislature of its activities, the amount of each award
3 granted, the cumulative total award amount, the number of
4 awards made by profession type and the county and
5 municipality where each health professional that received an
6 award practices in the state."
7 SECTION 6. REPEAL.--Sections 21-22D-2 and 21-22D-9 NMSA
8 1978 (being Laws 1995, Chapter 144, Sections 17 and 24) are
9 repealed. HHHC/HB 66/a
